{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"a5a6e851-b1fa-4baa-adfb-3392d26fb04d","content":"You're on **MSTest 3.8.2 / .NET 9**, which supports modern patterns. Here's the recommended approach:\n\n**Constructor injection** for `TestContext`, plus `[TestInitialize]` for both sync and async setup:\n\n```csharp\n[TestClass]\npublic class MyTests\n{\n    private readonly TestContext _testContext;\n    private MyService _service;\n\n    // TestContext injected via constructor (MSTest 3.x+)\n    public MyTests(TestContext testContext)\n    {\n        _testContext = testContext;\n\n        // Synchronous init here (runs before each test)\n        _service = new MyService();\n    }\n\n    // Async init (runs after constructor, before each test)\n    [TestInitialize]\n    public async Task SetupAsync()\n    {\n        await _service.ConnectAsync();\n    }\n\n    [TestMethod]\n    public void ExampleTest()\n    {\n        _testContext.WriteLine(\"Running test\");\n        Assert.IsNotNull(_service);\n    }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n- **Constructor** → sync init + `TestContext` injection (no property/setter needed)\n- **`[TestInitialize]`** → use for async setup (return `Task`)\n- Both run per-test. For one-time class setup, use `[ClassInitialize]` (static method)","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"981008c2-b1fe-4d6d-9df1-19c2ad7257c9","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"They're using MSTest 3.8.2 on .NET 9.0. Let me check what the modern MSTest patterns are for this version.\n\nIn MSTest v3+, the recommended approach is:\n\n1. **TestContext injection**: Use a constructor parameter or `public TestContext TestContext { get; set; }` property. In MSTest 3.x, constructor injection is supported.\n\n2. **Synchronous initialization**: Use `[TestInitialize]` attribute on a method.\n\n3. **Asynchronous initialization**: `[TestInitialize]` supports async methods (returning `Task`).\n\nActually, let me think about this more carefully for MSTest 3.8.2:\n\n\n- `TestContext` can be injected directly via constructor in MSTest 3.x\n- `[TestInitialize]` works for both sync and async methods (just return `Task` for async)\n- Both patterns can coexist in the same test class\n\nLet me put together a clear, practical example.","outputTokens":643,"requestId":"7C10:203FDB:2854FC0:2CB0753:69F94883"},"id":"52619b6e-88a3-4f25-95f6-2aff8d1d9143","timestamp":"2026-05-05T01:32:00.681Z","parentId":"93ab907d-ec51-49c9-a6db-56cd7bf3acd4"}
